import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists(): return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing: existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]: existing[ch][v] = html

# ── Leviticus 13 | mkt-christ ──────────────────────────────────────────────
# Typological levels: direct type | type | shadow | theme | revelation of God

NEW = {
  "13": {
    "1": "<p>Shadow: The LORD speaks the skin-disease diagnostic law to Aaron as well as Moses, implicating the entire priestly line. The diagnosis of impurity and the declaration of cleanness are the exclusive domain of the priest. <a class='ref' data-ref='Hebrews 4:14'>Hebrews 4:14</a>&ndash;<a class='ref' data-ref='Hebrews 4:16'>16</a> presents Jesus as the great high priest who &ldquo;has passed through the heavens&rdquo; and who can be approached with confidence. Where Levitical priests examined the body for physical impurity, Christ examines the heart and is both the diagnostician and the cure.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Shadow: Three Hebrew terms describe skin conditions that trigger priestly examination: <em>se'et</em> (elevation), <em>sapachat</em> (swelling), <em>baheret</em> (bright spot). The elaborate diagnostic system shows that YHWH takes the distinction between clean and impure seriously as a matter of cultic order. This precision anticipates the precision of Christ&rsquo;s atonement: <a class='ref' data-ref='Hebrews 9:14'>Hebrews 9:14</a> describes his blood as purifying &ldquo;our conscience from dead works to serve the living God&rdquo; &mdash; the cleansing is interior and complete, reaching what no Levitical rite could.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Shadow: Two diagnostic signs confirm impurity: white hair in the affected area and the skin appears deeper than the surrounding flesh. The priest &ldquo;pronounces him unclean&rdquo; (<em>ve-timme'o ha-kohen</em>) &mdash; the priestly declaration is performative, not merely descriptive. <a class='ref' data-ref='John 5:22'>John 5:22</a> states that the Father has given all judgment to the Son. The eschatological judgment &mdash; the final declaration of clean or impure before God &mdash; belongs to Christ, the ultimate priestly judge.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Theme: When the signs are ambiguous &mdash; bright white but not deeper, no white hairs &mdash; the priest quarantines the person for seven days. The seven-day waiting period mirrors the creation week: YHWH&rsquo;s rhythm of six-plus-one shapes even medical protocol. Theologically, this pause before judgment reflects divine patience. <a class='ref' data-ref='2 Peter 3:9'>2 Peter 3:9</a> grounds God&rsquo;s delay of judgment in the same patience: &ldquo;not wishing that any should perish, but that all should reach repentance.&rdquo;</p>",
    "5": "<p>Theme: On the seventh day the priest re-examines. If the condition is unchanged and has not spread, the quarantine is extended another seven days. The repeated examination embodies a principle of careful discernment before final verdict. <a class='ref' data-ref='1 Corinthians 4:5'>1 Corinthians 4:5</a> warns against premature judgment: &ldquo;Therefore do not pronounce judgment before the time, before the Lord comes, who will bring to light the things now hidden in darkness.&rdquo; The priest who waits anticipates the judge who waits for full disclosure.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Theme: After the second seven days, if the condition has faded and has not spread, the priest declares the person clean &mdash; it was only a rash (<em>mispachat</em>). The person must wash their garments and is then clean. The washing-of-garments as part of cleansing appears repeatedly in Leviticus and anticipates the NT image of <a class='ref' data-ref='Revelation 7:14'>Revelation 7:14</a>: those who &ldquo;have washed their robes and made them white in the blood of the Lamb.&rdquo; Physical washing of cloth foreshadows spiritual cleansing through Christ&rsquo;s sacrifice.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Shadow: If the rash spreads after the priest has declared the person clean, a second examination is required. The possibility of apparent cleansing followed by renewed spreading is a diagnostic reality in Leviticus and a spiritual reality in the NT. <a class='ref' data-ref='2 Peter 2:20'>2 Peter 2:20</a>&ndash;<a class='ref' data-ref='2 Peter 2:22'>22</a> warns of those who escape defilement only to return to it: &ldquo;The last state has become worse for them than the first.&rdquo; The spreading condition is worse than the original presentation.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Shadow: The priest examines the spreading rash and declares the person impure &mdash; it is tzara'at. The spreading criterion is the decisive factor throughout Leviticus 13. <a class='ref' data-ref='1 Corinthians 5:6'>1 Corinthians 5:6</a> applies the same logic to sin in the community: &ldquo;Do you not know that a little leaven leavens the whole lump?&rdquo; Spreading impurity must be named and addressed before it contaminates what is clean. Paul&rsquo;s application of this principle shows the Levitical boundary logic is not merely ritual but ethical.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Shadow: The case of established (<em>noshenet</em>) tzara'at is introduced. The diagnostic category shifts from ambiguous to unambiguous: a chronic, clearly established condition. The immediate priestly presentation required reflects the principle that known, entrenched impurity must be brought before God&rsquo;s representative. <a class='ref' data-ref='1 John 1:9'>1 John 1:9</a> calls for the same direct approach to Christ: &ldquo;If we confess our sins, he is faithful and just to forgive us our sins and to cleanse us from all unrighteousness.&rdquo;</p>",
    "10": "<p>Shadow: The three indicators of serious disease: white raised area, raw flesh visible in the elevation. Raw flesh (<em>michar chai</em>, &ldquo;living flesh&rdquo;) exposed within the diseased area signals active, ongoing disease &mdash; the wound has not healed over. <a class='ref' data-ref='Hebrews 10:26'>Hebrews 10:26</a>&ndash;<a class='ref' data-ref='Hebrews 10:27'>27</a> describes willful, ongoing sin after receiving knowledge of the truth as an open wound before God: &ldquo;a fearful expectation of judgment, and a fury of fire that will consume the adversaries.&rdquo;</p>",
    "11": "<p>Shadow: The established disease is declared impure without the seven-day quarantine &mdash; the priest declares immediately (<em>ve-timme'o ha-kohen... lo yisgor ki tameh hu</em>: &ldquo;the priest shall pronounce him unclean; he shall not quarantine him, for he is unclean&rdquo;). When the evidence is unambiguous, no extended deliberation is needed. This anticipates the clarity of divine judgment: <a class='ref' data-ref='Romans 1:20'>Romans 1:20</a> states that those who suppress the truth are &ldquo;without excuse&rdquo; &mdash; the evidence leaves no room for ambiguity.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Theme: The counterintuitive case: if the disease covers the entire body from head to foot, and the priest examines and finds it all white &mdash; he declares the person clean. Whole-body coverage means no boundary between diseased and healthy remains. Theologically this touches the paradox of total acknowledgment before God: <a class='ref' data-ref='Romans 3:23'>Romans 3:23</a> declares that &ldquo;all have sinned and fall short of the glory of God&rdquo; &mdash; when there is no pretense of partial righteousness, justification becomes possible (&ldquo;being justified freely by his grace,&rdquo; v.24).</p>",
    "13": "<p>Theme: The priest looks and finds that the disease has covered all of his body, and he pronounces him clean. The person &ldquo;has turned all white&rdquo; and is clean. This paradox is echoed in <a class='ref' data-ref='Luke 18:13'>Luke 18:13</a>&ndash;<a class='ref' data-ref='Luke 18:14'>14</a>: the tax collector who offers only &ldquo;God, be merciful to me, a sinner!&rdquo; goes home justified, while the Pharisee who catalogs his righteousness does not. The person who is entirely covered in acknowledged unworthiness is declared clean.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Shadow: But whenever raw flesh appears, he is impure. The transition from covered-all-white (clean) back to visible raw flesh (impure) creates a theologically significant dynamic: ongoing exposure of active sin, not its acknowledged presence, is the issue. <a class='ref' data-ref='1 John 1:8'>1 John 1:8</a>: &ldquo;If we say we have no sin, we deceive ourselves, and the truth is not in us.&rdquo; Acknowledged sin under Christ&rsquo;s covering is different from unacknowledged, actively festering sin.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Shadow: The priest examines the raw flesh and declares him unclean. The raw flesh (<em>basar chai</em>) is impure. The image of exposed flesh as the diagnostic sign of active disease parallels the NT&rsquo;s use of &ldquo;flesh&rdquo; (<em>sarx</em>) as the seat of the unregenerate self. <a class='ref' data-ref='Galatians 5:19'>Galatians 5:19</a>&ndash;<a class='ref' data-ref='Galatians 5:21'>21</a> catalogs &ldquo;works of the flesh&rdquo; as the active manifestation of the impure condition that requires Christ&rsquo;s Spirit to replace.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Theme: If the raw flesh turns again and changes to white, the person returns to the priest. The possibility of the raw flesh healing over and the person becoming clean again implies that the diagnostic process is ongoing, not a single one-time verdict. This resonates with the NT pattern of sanctification: <a class='ref' data-ref='2 Corinthians 3:18'>2 Corinthians 3:18</a> describes believers being &ldquo;transformed into the same image from one degree of glory to another.&rdquo; The clean-unclean status can change as spiritual condition changes.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Theme: The priest examines the condition again; if it has turned white, the priest declares the person clean. The circular possibility &mdash; impure becomes clean, clean becomes impure, impure becomes clean again &mdash; models the pastoral reality of spiritual fluctuation. <a class='ref' data-ref='1 John 2:1'>1 John 2:1</a>&ndash;<a class='ref' data-ref='1 John 2:2'>2</a>: &ldquo;if anyone does sin, we have an advocate with the Father, Jesus Christ the righteous. He is the propitiation for our sins.&rdquo; The advocate-priest is available for re-examination and re-declaration at each point of return.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Shadow: The boil (<em>shechin</em>) that heals and then develops tzara'at symptoms introduces the category of secondary infection &mdash; disease that emerges from a site of previous wounding. Past suffering or sin can become the location from which new spiritual disease spreads. <a class='ref' data-ref='Hebrews 12:15'>Hebrews 12:15</a> warns of &ldquo;a root of bitterness&rdquo; that &ldquo;springs up and causes trouble, and by it many become defiled.&rdquo; Old wounds that are not brought to Christ become sources of ongoing contamination.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Shadow: A white elevation or reddish-white spot appears at the site of the old boil. The visual signs are the same as the primary tzara'at criteria. This teaches that the same diagnostic principles apply regardless of the disease&rsquo;s origin &mdash; whether primary or secondary, the signs of serious impurity are identifiable. <a class='ref' data-ref='James 1:14'>James 1:14</a>&ndash;<a class='ref' data-ref='James 1:15'>15</a> traces sin&rsquo;s anatomy: desire &rarr; enticement &rarr; sin &rarr; death. The progression is diagnosable at each stage.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Shadow: The same two criteria apply: appearance deeper than surrounding skin, white hair present = tzara'at; the priest declares impure. Consistency of diagnostic standards regardless of the wound&rsquo;s location embodies the principle that YHWH does not apply different standards to different people. <a class='ref' data-ref='Acts 10:34'>Acts 10:34</a>&ndash;<a class='ref' data-ref='Acts 10:35'>35</a>: &ldquo;God shows no partiality, but in every nation anyone who fears him and does what is right is acceptable to him.&rdquo;</p>",
    "21": "<p>Theme: But if on examination the spot has no white hair and is not deeper than the skin but has faded, the priest quarantines for seven days again. The same ambiguous-case protocol applies to secondary diseases. The seven-day waiting rhythm persists throughout all the diagnostic categories, reinforcing that God&rsquo;s timing is consistent: <a class='ref' data-ref='Isaiah 28:16'>Isaiah 28:16</a> (&ldquo;whoever believes will not be in haste&rdquo;) and <a class='ref' data-ref='Habakkuk 2:3'>Habakkuk 2:3</a> (&ldquo;if it seems slow, wait for it; it will surely come&rdquo;) both affirm the wisdom of waiting for YHWH&rsquo;s timing.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Shadow: If the spot spreads during the quarantine, the priest declares it tzara'at &mdash; impure. The spreading criterion recurs as the decisive marker of serious disease. <a class='ref' data-ref='2 Timothy 2:17'>2 Timothy 2:17</a> uses the same image for false teaching: it &ldquo;will spread like gangrene&rdquo; (<em>hos gangraina nomein hexei</em>). The visual metaphor of unstoppable spreading disease was available in antiquity precisely because skin conditions like tzara'at were observed and feared for their spreading character.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Revelation of God: If the spot has not spread but is faded, it is only the scar of the boil (<em>tzevet ha-shechin</em>), and the priest declares it clean. YHWH&rsquo;s diagnostic law distinguishes between a scar (healed, benign, not impure) and active disease. God does not treat past healed wounds as ongoing impurity. This reveals a God of precise, not punitive, judgment: <a class='ref' data-ref='Psalm 103:12'>Psalm 103:12</a> &mdash; &ldquo;as far as the east is from the west, so far does he remove our transgressions from us.&rdquo; Healed wounds are clean.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Shadow: The burn case (<em>mikevah-esh</em>) parallels the boil case. A burn site that develops white or reddish-white spots triggers the same diagnostic protocol. The association of fire with judgment and purification is prominent throughout Scripture. <a class='ref' data-ref='1 Corinthians 3:13'>1 Corinthians 3:13</a>: each person&rsquo;s work &ldquo;will be revealed by fire, and the fire will test what sort of work each one has done.&rdquo; Sites of testing and trial are also sites where impurity may be uncovered or confirmed.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Shadow: The diagnostic criteria for the burn case: if the spot has white hair and appears deeper than the skin, it is tzara'at breaking out in the burn &mdash; declared impure. The &ldquo;breaking out&rdquo; (<em>porach</em>) of disease at the burn site suggests something latent surfacing under the trauma of wounding. <a class='ref' data-ref='Romans 7:8'>Romans 7:8</a>: &ldquo;sin, seizing an opportunity through the commandment, produced in me all kinds of covetousness.&rdquo; Law and testing reveal what was latent.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Theme: But if no white hair is in the spot and it is not lower than the skin but is faded, the priest quarantines for seven days. The burn-case protocol mirrors the boil-case exactly, reflecting the consistent application of divine standards. <a class='ref' data-ref='Romans 2:11'>Romans 2:11</a>: &ldquo;For God shows no partiality.&rdquo; The same diagnostic logic applies to everyone regardless of how they were wounded.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Shadow: On the seventh day the priest examines again; if it has spread in the skin, the priest declares it tzara'at &mdash; impure. The spread is the decisive confirmation. <a class='ref' data-ref='Hebrews 3:13'>Hebrews 3:13</a> applies this principle to the church: &ldquo;exhort one another every day... that none of you may be hardened by the deceitfulness of sin.&rdquo; Regular community examination &mdash; the seven-day rhythm as a metaphor for continual mutual accountability &mdash; prevents undetected spread.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Revelation of God: If the spot has not spread in the skin but has faded, it is the swelling from the burn (<em>se'et ha-mikevah</em>) and the priest declares clean &mdash; it is a scar of the burn. Again the scar is distinguished from disease. A wound that has genuinely healed is not held against the person. This reflects YHWH&rsquo;s character as <a class='ref' data-ref='Micah 7:18'>Micah 7:18</a> describes: one who &ldquo;does not retain his anger forever, because he delights in steadfast love.&rdquo; Past suffering, when healed, does not define the person&rsquo;s standing before God.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Shadow: Disease of the head or beard (<em>nefeq</em>, scale/itch) introduces a distinct diagnostic category with different visual criteria: yellow thin hair rather than white hair. The head and beard are sites of honor and authority in the ancient world &mdash; the beard signified manhood and status. Disease here strikes at identity and dignity. <a class='ref' data-ref='Isaiah 53:3'>Isaiah 53:3</a> describes the Suffering Servant as &ldquo;despised and rejected by men,&rdquo; his dignity stripped away &mdash; taking on the reproach of the diseased and marginalized.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Shadow: The priest examines and if the appearance is deeper than the skin and yellow thin hair is in it, the priest declares it impure. The specific diagnostic criteria for scalp disease mirrors the precision of divine discernment. <a class='ref' data-ref='Hebrews 4:12'>Hebrews 4:12</a>&ndash;<a class='ref' data-ref='Hebrews 4:13'>13</a>: &ldquo;the word of God is living and active... discerning the thoughts and intentions of the heart. And no creature is hidden from his sight.&rdquo; The divine diagnostic penetrates to the exact location and character of the condition.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Theme: If the scale appears no deeper than the skin and no black hair is in it, the priest quarantines for seven days. The absence of dark hair (healthy hair) is a negative diagnostic sign here. The quarantine acknowledges uncertainty while maintaining protective separation. <a class='ref' data-ref='Matthew 13:24'>Matthew 13:24</a>&ndash;<a class='ref' data-ref='Matthew 13:30'>30</a>: the parable of wheat and tares counsels against premature separation: &ldquo;let both grow together until the harvest... then I will tell the reapers, gather the weeds first.&rdquo; Careful discernment waits for clarity.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Shadow: On the seventh day the priest examines the scale. If it has not spread, no yellow hair, and appears no deeper than the skin, the person shaves &mdash; but not the scale itself &mdash; and is quarantined another seven days. The command not to shave the infected spot itself preserves the diagnostic evidence for re-examination. Thoroughness in evaluation before final verdict. <a class='ref' data-ref='1 Thessalonians 5:21'>1 Thessalonians 5:21</a>: &ldquo;test everything; hold fast what is good.&rdquo;</p>",
    "33": "<p>Theme: The instruction to shave but spare the scale, then quarantine again, emphasizes that ambiguous cases require sustained attention. The person is shaved to make the affected area clearly visible but is not yet declared clean. The process of sanctification similarly involves progressive exposure of what needs to be addressed: <a class='ref' data-ref='Philippians 1:6'>Philippians 1:6</a> &mdash; &ldquo;he who began a good work in you will bring it to completion at the day of Jesus Christ.&rdquo;</p>",
    "34": "<p>Theme: On the seventh day the priest examines again; if the scale has not spread and appears no deeper, the priest declares the person clean. The person washes garments and is clean. The washing of garments marks this transition as it did in v.6. The repeated washing-garments formula throughout Leviticus 13&ndash;14 points to the NT&rsquo;s pervasive garment-of-righteousness imagery: <a class='ref' data-ref='Zechariah 3:4'>Zechariah 3:4</a> (Joshua reclothed in clean garments), <a class='ref' data-ref='Isaiah 61:10'>Isaiah 61:10</a> (robe of righteousness), <a class='ref' data-ref='Revelation 19:8'>Revelation 19:8</a> (fine linen, bright and pure).</p>",
    "35": "<p>Shadow: But if the scale spreads in the skin after the declaration of cleanness, the priest must examine again. The post-declaration spreading creates a more serious situation than the original presentation &mdash; cleanness declared and then revoked is a serious escalation. <a class='ref' data-ref='Hebrews 6:4'>Hebrews 6:4</a>&ndash;<a class='ref' data-ref='Hebrews 6:6'>6</a> addresses the analogous spiritual situation: those who have been enlightened and tasted the heavenly gift, then fallen away, face a more severe judgment than those who never received the initial grace.</p>",
    "36": "<p>Shadow: If the scale has spread, the priest does not need to look for yellow hair &mdash; the person is impure. The spreading overrides the absence of other diagnostic signs; one conclusive sign is sufficient for a final verdict. <a class='ref' data-ref='James 2:10'>James 2:10</a>: &ldquo;whoever keeps the whole law but fails in one point has become guilty of all of it.&rdquo; The logic of law&rsquo;s integrity: one point of failure is conclusive.</p>",
    "37": "<p>Revelation of God: But if the scale appears to be stationary and black hair has grown in it, the scale has healed &mdash; the person is clean, and the priest declares clean. New black hair (healthy hair) growing in the affected area is a sign of healing and restoration. YHWH&rsquo;s diagnostic system recognizes genuine healing when it occurs. <a class='ref' data-ref='Isaiah 40:31'>Isaiah 40:31</a>: &ldquo;they who wait for the LORD shall renew their strength; they shall mount up with wings like eagles.&rdquo; New growth in the place of old disease is the sign of divine renewal.</p>",
    "38": "<p>Revelation of God: The harmless bright-spot case (<em>bohaq</em>, vv.38-39): bright white spots on a man or woman&rsquo;s skin are examined and declared a harmless rash &mdash; clean. Not every visible condition is impure. YHWH&rsquo;s law is not paranoid or overzealous; it distinguishes between alarming appearance and actual disease. This restraint in judgment models the divine character: <a class='ref' data-ref='Psalm 103:14'>Psalm 103:14</a> &mdash; &ldquo;he knows our frame; he remembers that we are dust.&rdquo; God does not treat every human weakness as culpable.</p>",
    "39": "<p>Revelation of God: The priest examines and finds the spots faded dull white &mdash; it is only <em>bohaq</em>, harmless. The priest declares clean. This is one of the shortest diagnostic rulings in the chapter, yet it carries significant theological weight: precision in judgment means acquitting the innocent as well as convicting the guilty. <a class='ref' data-ref='Proverbs 17:15'>Proverbs 17:15</a>: &ldquo;he who justifies the wicked and he who condemns the righteous are both alike an abomination to the LORD.&rdquo; The priest who declares clean what is clean honors God equally with the priest who declares impure what is impure.</p>",
    "40": "<p>Revelation of God: Ordinary male-pattern baldness (<em>qerach</em>, from the back of the head) is declared clean &mdash; not a diagnostic condition at all. The explicit inclusion of baldness as non-impure prevents the extension of the diagnostic system beyond its proper scope. This reflects a principle Christ invokes in <a class='ref' data-ref='Matthew 23:24'>Matthew 23:24</a> against the Pharisees: &ldquo;straining out a gnat and swallowing a camel&rdquo; &mdash; hyper-extension of purity rules to cover what YHWH never intended.</p>",
    "41": "<p>Revelation of God: Baldness from the forehead (<em>gibeach</em>) is similarly clean. The two types of baldness (back-of-head, forehead) are both explicitly cleared. The law is not a tool of social stigma against those with common physical variations. <a class='ref' data-ref='1 Samuel 16:7'>1 Samuel 16:7</a>: &ldquo;the LORD sees not as man sees: man looks on the outward appearance, but the LORD looks on the heart.&rdquo; Leviticus 13 applies this principle in reverse: natural appearance that is commonly alarming is cleared by divine declaration.</p>",
    "42": "<p>Shadow: But if in the bald area a reddish-white diseased spot appears, it is tzara'at breaking out in the bald area. The vulnerable, exposed scalp becomes a site where disease can break out. Sites of natural vulnerability are not themselves impure, but they require watchfulness. <a class='ref' data-ref='1 Peter 5:8'>1 Peter 5:8</a>: &ldquo;be sober-minded; be watchful. Your adversary the devil prowls around like a roaring lion, seeking someone to devour.&rdquo; Vulnerability is not sin but calls for vigilance.</p>",
    "43": "<p>Shadow: The priest examines the bald-area spot; if the reddish-white elevation looks like tzara'at in the skin elsewhere, the person is impure. The diagnostic standards are consistent regardless of location: head, beard, bald scalp all receive the same criteria. <a class='ref' data-ref='Romans 2:11'>Romans 2:11</a>: &ldquo;God shows no partiality.&rdquo; The uniformity of the diagnostic law foreshadows the uniformity of Christ&rsquo;s judgment across all people.</p>",
    "44": "<p>Shadow: The man is diseased (<em>tzaru'a</em>), he is impure, and the priest shall surely pronounce him impure &mdash; his disease is on his head. The formulation &ldquo;his disease is on his head&rdquo; (&ldquo;be-rosho nig'o&rdquo;) suggests the disease has claimed the most visible, identity-defining part of the person. Sin at its most serious is not peripheral but central. <a class='ref' data-ref='Romans 1:28'>Romans 1:28</a>&ndash;<a class='ref' data-ref='Romans 1:31'>31</a>: the catalog of minds given over to impurity culminates in the corruption of the reasoning capacity itself &mdash; the most distinctively human faculty.</p>",
    "45": "<p>Direct type: The exclusion protocol for the diagnosed person: torn clothes, disheveled hair, covered lip, and the cry &ldquo;impure! impure!&rdquo; (<em>tameh tameh</em>). All four actions are mourning gestures in the Hebrew tradition &mdash; the diseased person inhabits the social role of the already-dead. <a class='ref' data-ref='Hebrews 13:12'>Hebrews 13:12</a>&ndash;<a class='ref' data-ref='Hebrews 13:13'>13</a> explicitly invokes this: &ldquo;Jesus also suffered <em>outside the gate</em> in order to sanctify the people through his own blood. Therefore let us go to him <em>outside the camp</em> and bear the reproach he endured.&rdquo; Christ bore the outcasted person&rsquo;s exclusion, and his people are called to share it.</p>",
    "46": "<p>Direct type: &ldquo;He shall remain impure as long as he has the disease. He is impure. He shall live alone. His dwelling shall be outside the camp.&rdquo; Outside the camp (<em>michutz la-machaneh</em>) is the zone of total exclusion from YHWH&rsquo;s presence in the sanctuary. It is also where the sin-offering carcasses were burned (<a class='ref' data-ref='Leviticus 4:12'>Lev 4:12</a>, 21; <a class='ref' data-ref='Leviticus 16:27'>16:27</a>). Jesus was crucified &ldquo;outside the gate&rdquo; of Jerusalem, identifying himself with both the excluded diseased person and the sin-bearing sacrifice. <a class='ref' data-ref='Hebrews 13:12'>Hebrews 13:12</a> makes this typological equation explicit.</p>",
    "47": "<p>Type: The garment-disease section (vv.47-59) addresses mold, mildew, or fungal growth in wool, linen, or leather. Garments in Hebrew thought are closely tied to identity, honor, and covering. Clothing covers shame, signals status, and mediates social identity. <a class='ref' data-ref='Isaiah 64:6'>Isaiah 64:6</a>: &ldquo;all our righteous deeds are like a polluted garment&rdquo; (<em>ke-begged 'iddim</em>) &mdash; even the best human moral effort is presented as a garment requiring diagnosis. The garment-disease law anticipates the need for a different garment entirely.</p>",
    "48": "<p>Type: Whether the disease is in warp or woof, in linen or wool, in leather or anything made of leather &mdash; the same diagnostic protocol applies. The comprehensive list (all fabric types, all weaving orientations, all leather goods) ensures no garment escapes the law. <a class='ref' data-ref='Romans 3:19'>Romans 3:19</a>&ndash;<a class='ref' data-ref='Romans 3:20'>20</a>: the law speaks &ldquo;so that every mouth may be stopped, and the whole world may be held accountable to God.&rdquo; No human covering escapes divine examination.</p>",
    "49": "<p>Type: A greenish or reddish spot in the garment (or skin or warp or woof) is tzara'at and must be shown to the priest. The discoloration that triggers examination &mdash; green or red growth &mdash; is caused by mold and fungal organisms (Aspergillus, Cladosporium for green; Neurospora, Fusarium for red). The garment must be presented to the priest, just as the person must be. <a class='ref' data-ref='Zechariah 3:3'>Zechariah 3:3</a>: Joshua the high priest stands before the angel wearing &ldquo;filthy garments&rdquo; &mdash; the condition of his garments represents the condition he brings before God.</p>",
    "50": "<p>Type: The priest examines the disease in the garment and quarantines it for seven days. The same seven-day waiting rhythm for garments as for persons reinforces that the diagnostic logic applies to all that belongs to a person &mdash; their coverings are subject to the same holiness standard as their bodies. <a class='ref' data-ref='Revelation 3:18'>Revelation 3:18</a>: Christ counsels Laodicea to &ldquo;buy from me... white garments so that you may clothe yourself and the shame of your nakedness may not be seen.&rdquo; The inadequacy of current covering is the starting point for seeking Christ&rsquo;s clothing.</p>",
    "51": "<p>Type: On the seventh day the priest examines; if the disease has spread in the garment, it is a spreading tzara'at &mdash; impure. The spreading criterion applies to garments as to skin. The garment that has been contaminated and continues to spread contamination must be destroyed: &ldquo;it is a malignant tzara'at.&rdquo; <a class='ref' data-ref='Jude 23'>Jude 23</a>: &ldquo;save others by snatching them out of the fire; to others show mercy with fear, hating even the garment stained by the flesh.&rdquo; The infected garment is a direct symbol Jude employs for sin&rsquo;s contamination.</p>",
    "52": "<p>Type: The priest shall burn the garment &mdash; warp, woof, wool, linen, or leather &mdash; in which the disease has spread. It is a malignant tzara'at; it shall be burned in fire. The burning of the infected garment recalls the burning of the sin-offering outside the camp (Lev 4:12). Both are acts of purification through destruction of what cannot be made clean. <a class='ref' data-ref='1 Corinthians 3:15'>1 Corinthians 3:15</a>: &ldquo;if anyone&rsquo;s work is burned up, he will suffer loss, though he himself will be saved, but only as through fire.&rdquo;</p>",
    "53": "<p>Theme: If the priest examines and the disease has not spread in the garment, the priest orders the garment washed and quarantined another seven days. The possibility of a second chance &mdash; wash, wait, re-examine &mdash; for garments as for persons reflects YHWH&rsquo;s consistency: every possible path to cleanness is pursued before destruction is ordered. <a class='ref' data-ref='Ezekiel 18:23'>Ezekiel 18:23</a>: &ldquo;Have I any pleasure in the death of the wicked, declares the Lord GOD, and not rather that he should turn from his way and live?&rdquo;</p>",
    "54": "<p>Theme: The priest commands the washing of the infected article and quarantines it for a further seven days. The double examination before any verdict against the garment emphasizes the patience and thoroughness of divine judgment. <a class='ref' data-ref='2 Peter 3:9'>2 Peter 3:9</a>: &ldquo;The Lord is not slow to fulfill his promise as some count slowness, but is patient toward you, not wishing that any should perish.&rdquo; The seven-day quarantines embody this patience at the level of cultic ritual.</p>",
    "55": "<p>Type: After the second examination, if the diseased spot has not changed its appearance even though the disease has not spread, the garment is burned &mdash; whether the blemish is on the inside or outside. A disease that neither spreads nor heals after washing and waiting is pronounced malignant by non-change: the static, unresponsive spot is as condemned as the spreading one. <a class='ref' data-ref='Matthew 25:24'>Matthew 25:24</a>&ndash;<a class='ref' data-ref='Matthew 25:30'>30</a>: the servant who buried his talent and did nothing with it faces the same judgment as one who actively squandered it.</p>",
    "56": "<p>Theme: But if the priest examines and the disease has faded after the washing, he shall tear the spot out of the garment. Surgical removal of the contaminated area, preserving the rest, is the preferred outcome when possible. This models the principle of <a class='ref' data-ref='Matthew 5:29'>Matthew 5:29</a>&ndash;<a class='ref' data-ref='Matthew 5:30'>30</a>: &ldquo;if your right eye causes you to sin, tear it out and throw it away... if your right hand causes you to sin, cut it off and throw it away.&rdquo; Radical removal of the contaminated part to preserve the whole is better than total destruction.</p>",
    "57": "<p>Shadow: But if the disease appears again in the garment after the spot was torn out, it is spreading and the whole garment must be burned. Recurrence after partial treatment requires escalation to total destruction. The partial solution (tearing out the spot) failed because the contamination was deeper than the visible spot. <a class='ref' data-ref='Romans 7:21'>Romans 7:21</a>&ndash;<a class='ref' data-ref='Romans 7:24'>24</a>: Paul&rsquo;s anguished account of sin&rsquo;s recurrence despite his efforts &mdash; &ldquo;Wretched man that I am! Who will deliver me from this body of death?&rdquo; &mdash; models the experience of recurring contamination that outstrips partial remedies.</p>",
    "58": "<p>Type: But if the disease disappears from the garment after washing and it is washed a second time, it shall be clean. The garment can be genuinely cleansed if the disease actually responds to washing. <a class='ref' data-ref='Revelation 7:14'>Revelation 7:14</a>: the great multitude &ldquo;have washed their robes and made them white in the blood of the Lamb.&rdquo; The washed-clean garment is one of Revelation&rsquo;s central images for the saints who have been genuinely purified through Christ&rsquo;s atoning blood &mdash; the washing that Levitical water anticipated but could not accomplish.</p>",
    "59": "<p>Type: &ldquo;This is the law for a case of leprous disease in a garment of wool or linen, either in warp or woof, or anything of leather, to pronounce it clean or unclean.&rdquo; The summary formula (<em>zot torat nega ha-tzara'at begued...</em>) closes the chapter as it closes other sections of Leviticus (cf. 6:9, 14, 25; 7:1, 11; 11:46; 12:7). The double purpose &mdash; to pronounce clean (<em>le-taher</em>) or to pronounce impure (<em>le-tamme'</em>) &mdash; names both outcomes as legitimate functions of the law. <a class='ref' data-ref='Romans 3:20'>Romans 3:20</a>: &ldquo;through the law comes knowledge of sin.&rdquo; The law&rsquo;s diagnostic function prepares the ground for the gospel&rsquo;s healing function.</p>"
  }
}

